@node "Past" "Past"
This is the fourth release of this program. Here's a quick resume of how the
program came about.

 - Originally intended to write a virtual pet program in response to Amiga
   Format's plea for a decent one, and the promise of £50.

 - Started graphics for a program called "Tam" (for Tamogotchi); animation
   frames for a cartoon rabbit.

 - Programming begun; rabbit runs after mouse pointer.

 - Amiga Format complain about flood of Tamogotchi programs, and refuse to
   review any more.

 - Damn.

 - Start animation frames for Gorman Fish (the history of The Fish is far
   too complex and long-winded to explain; suffice to say, it will only be
   revealed upon explicit request).

 - Without any warning, I suddenly find I have developed a fully-working
   virtual pet, albeit with very few features.

 - Messed about with code every now and again, in case any ideas arose.

 - No ideas arose.

 - Began FishEditor, in lieu of anything better to do with it.

 - WindowFish suggested, and the GormanFishtank program was torn to pieces
   and re-assembled to run in a window.

 - Released on my @{"website" link "The author" 0} sometime in late 1999.

 - Submitted to Amiga Format in February 2000.

 - Included on the last cover CD, and won £50 for the best reader
   contribution.

 Started development:    6/98
 Finished development:   I have no idea.
 Total development time: 4 years and counting.
@endnode

@node "Future" "Future"
As it stands, Gorman Fishtank is nowhere near finished.  I still need to:

 - finish the buttons
 - add more pointer actions
 - add more features
 - add loads more secrets
 - change a few samples
 - load/save fish

I'm also developing a few related projects:

 - WindowFish - Fishtank in a window; slightly behind this in development
 - FishEditor - Design your own fish.

Gorman Fishtank will only ever run on a PAL low-res screen.  It is written in
Blitz Basic, and Blitz really doesn't co-operate with advanced hardware like
graphics cards, sound cards or fast accelerators.  It often refuses to work
with such advanced technologies as electricity.
@endnode

